The genus 

Agave

belongs to the family 
Agavaceae
and is distributed throughout tropical and sub-tropical regions of the world. This genus has more than 400 species growing in arid and semi-arid climates. 
Agaves
are often referred to as hardy century plant, rough century plant or wild century plant in recognition of their ability to grow in dry lands. The name century plant implies a vast array of uses and applications of 
Agaves
(

). Human interest in the genus 

Agave

extends back to an ancient era when 
agua miel
, a fermented beverage, was extracted from these plants. 

Agave
plants

have been used as a source of fiber, food and beverages (

; 

; 

). More recently, 

Agave
species

have also been investigated for their potential as nutraceuticals, prebiotics, natural sweeteners and biofuels (

; 

; 

; 

; 

).

Saponins are glycosides of triterpenes or steroids with a number of bioactivities like anticancer, adjuvant, immunostimulant, antiinflammatory, antimicrobial, hypocholesterolemic and antioxidant properties (

; 

). Saponins are receiving much attention from chemists and biologists globally for new drug discovery (

; Gl-Ustndag and 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). There have also been substantial developments in the phytochemistry and bioactivity studies of saponins of 

Agave

in the last two decades. The present review is a comprehensive description of the sapogenins and saponins reported from 

Agave
species

, their structural peculiarities, methods of extraction, isolation and chemical profiling, spectroscopic properties and biological activities. The literature has been searched using Scifinder 

and the articles published 1970 onwards have been reviewed. The aim of this review is to provide a perspective of the research on steroidal sapogenins and saponins of 

Agave

.

A spectrum of primary and secondary metabolites has been reported from different 

Agave
species.

The primary metabolites include carbohydrates (

; 

) and processed 

Agave

syrups are increasingly recognized as natural sweeteners, functional foods and prebiotics (

; 

; 

). 

Agave
plants

contain secondary metabolites of diverse classes, such as steroidal sapogenins and saponins, sterols (

), flavonoids (

; 

; 

; 

), homoisoflavonoids (

; 

), phenolic acids (

), tannins (

; 

), volatile coumarins (

), long chain alkanes, fatty acids and alcohols (

; 

; 

). Steroidal sapogenins and saponins are perhaps the most widely studied compounds in this genus and also the focus of this review.

Furostanol glycosides of
Agave
can be categorized as 22-hydroxy or 22-methoxy furostanols. The latter are artifacts generated from the former as a result of extraction and processing of the plant materials with methanol (
; Yokosuka et al., 2009). These compounds, on treatment with b -glucosidase, give the corresponding spirostanol saponins and b -D-glucose (Yokosuka et al., 2009;
). Compound 118 , for example, gives 36 after enzymatic hydrolysis (
). Table 3 gives the details of furostanol glycosides of
Agave
.

The majority of the extraction procedures for saponins of 

Agave

involve classical methods such as Soxhlet extraction (

) and maceration (

; 

; 

, 

; 

). The choice of the extraction solvents is also limited as the saponins dissolve in polar solvents only. Hence, methanol (

; 

; 

; 

; Yokosuka et al., 2009; 

) and methanol (or ethanol)-water combinations (

, 

; 

) are generally employed for extraction. The choice of solvent also depends upon the probability of artifact formation. Methanol, for example, converts 22-hydroxyl furostanol glycosides into their respective 22-methoxyl derivatives (Yokosuka et al., 2009). The plant material is defatted with hexane prior to extraction in some cases (

).

Further, the fractionation of the crude extracts may involve a number of strategies to obtain saponin-rich fractions. The crude extracts are partitioned with hexane, chloroform, ethyl acetate and 
n
-butanol sequentially to yield fractions of different polarity. Sapogenins and saponins are generally concentrated in ethyl acetate and 
n
-butanol fractions, respectively (

; 

; 

, 

; 

). Saponins can also be precipitated from the crude extract by adding an excess of acetone (

). Enrichment of the saponins is also achieved by vacuum liquid chromatography over reversed phase silica gel (

, 

), column chromatography over macroporous resin (

, 2009; 

; 

), or size exclusion column chromatography using Sephadex LH-20 (

; 

).

Saponins are isolated from the crude extracts by size exclusion chromatography followed by normal phase silica gel chromatography (

; 

). Final purification of the compounds is done by column chromatography over normal or reverse phase silica gel (

; 

; 

; 

; 

), droplet counter current chromatography (DCCC) in descending mode (

) and semi-preparative high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or medium pressure liquid chromatography (MPLC) (

).

A classical approach for isolation of sapogenins involves acidic hydrolysis of the pulverized plant material or the crude extracts. The hydrolysate is then neutralized and extracted with organic solvents. The organic layers are then subjected to various chromatographic steps to yield pure compounds. This approach also involves conversion of saponins (glycosides) to sapogenins (aglycones) (

; 

). However, it is possible that the hydrolysis products are not natural sapogenins but are artifacts. These artifacts may change depending upon the saponin(s), as well as the hydrolysis conditions including temperature, time and solvent used (

). Preparative thin layer chromatography (TLC) over silica gel is also used for the isolation of sapogenins at analytical scale (

).

Hecogenin (
1
) is reported from several species of 

Agave

and is an important precursor in the chemical synthesis of steroid hormones (

). It is one of the most economically-important sapogenins reported from this genus. Therefore, several technologies have been developed over the years for fast and convenient isolation of hecogenin (
1
) from 

Agave
plants

. It has also been isolated from sisal waste (

Agave sisalana

leaves, after removal of fibers) in five simple steps. Sisal waste is refluxed (100 
C
) with distilled water for 3 h to obtain a crude sisal waste extract. This extract is then suspended in ethanol-water (8:2) and polysaccharides are precipitated out. The enriched extract is concentrated and partitioned with ethyl acetate. The organic layer is concentrated and subsequently hydrolyzed in the presence of hydrochloric acid/ ethanol. The hydrolyzed reaction mixture is neutralized using sodium hydroxide and again extracted with ethyl acetate. The ethyl acetate layer is dried to obtain pure hecogenin (
1
) with a yield of 
460 mg
/kg of sisal waste (

).

