Structure elucidation of saponins involve determination of both units present in the structure viz. the sapogenin and the sugar moiety (
). The number of sapogenin nuclei reported from
Agave
is limited, and identification involves trivial techniques such as co-TLC with reference standards and comparison of spectroscopic data with literature values. However, as the number of sugar units and branching points increase, structure elucidation becomes increasingly difficult. Hence, the use of chemical methods as well as advanced spectral techniques for complete and unambiguous structure elucidation are required (
).

Hecogenin ( 1 ) has a molecular ion peak at m/z 430. Its base peak at m/z 139 is characteristic of the spiroketal moiety present in the structure. Fig. S2 shows generation of the base peak ion from the molecular ion of hecogenin ( 1 ). Other significant fragment ions are also present. Saturated monohydroxyspirostanes, such as tigogenin ( 13 , M
at m/z 416), has prominent fragments at m/z 347, 302, 287, 273 and 139 (
). The mass spectrum (MS) of saturated dihydroxyspirostanes with hydroxyl groups located on rings A, B or C as in ruizgenin ( 19 , M
at m/z 432) also have significant fragment ions at m/z 318, 303, 300, 289, 285, 271 and 139. Similarly, MS of the monounsaturated dihydroxyspirostane type of sapogenins (yuccagenin, 24 , M
at m/z 430) have fragment ions at m/z 316, 301, 298, 287, 283, 269 and 139 (
;
).

As is the case of sapogenins, mass spectrometry is also used to decipher the identity of sugars present in the saponins. The loss of various monosaccharide units from a saponin molecule generates the fragmentation peaks of a characteristic molecular weight. For example, the loss of a pentose moiety gives a fragment with mass [M-132] units. Similarly, loss of 146 and 162 mass units depicts cleavage of deoxyhexose (rhamnose) and hexose (glucose or galactose) moieties, respectively. 
