Glycosylation at particular position(s) of sapogenins brings about a downfield shift in the 1 H and 13 C NMR signals of the respective protons and carbons. For example, glycosylation of the 3-OH moiety in agavoside A ( 29 ) shifts the H/C-3 signals to d H 3.93 and d C 77.0. These signals in the aglycone (hecogenin, 1 ) appear at d H 3.44 and d C 70.7 (Jin et al., 2003). Similarly, in chlorogenin 6- O - b - D-glucopyranoside ( 31 ), glycosylation of the 6-OH brings about a downfield shift 11.1 ppm C-6 (
). Further, the connection between the sapogenin and the sugar chain was established by the HMBC correlations between a) the anomeric proton and the carbons of the aglycone and b) protons of the aglycone and anomeric carbon of the sugar (
;
, 2009). In the case of magueyoside A, a NOE correlation between anomeric proton of the first sugar and the H-3 of aglycone confirmed the placement of the oligosaccharide chain at C-3 (
). In the case of furostanol glycosides, HMBC cross peak was observed between the anomeric proton of glucopyranosyl moiety and C-26 of the aglycone. Further, ROESY correlations between the anomeric proton and H 2 -26 confirmed the glycosylation position as C-26 (
).

Anomeric proton and carbon resonances were observed in a well defined region ( d H 4.4 to 6.1 and d C 98 to 109). The broad singlets and doublets of anomeric protons were linked to their respective carbons on the basis of HMQC or HSQC correlations. These signals were then used to determine the number of monosaccharides present in a saponin molecule. A complete assignment of the glycosidic protons was achieved by 1 H- 1 H COSY, 1D-TOCSY and 1D-ROESY experiments. Further, HMQC or HSQC helped establish the C-H connectivity (
;
;
;
).

