Apart from spectroscopic techniques, chemical methods are also of general applicability in structural characterization of sapogenins and saponins purified from 

Agave

. For sapogenins, chemical methods are trivially used for identification. For example, catalytic hydrogenation of yuccagenin (
24
) over Adam s catalyst yielded gitogenin (
15
) (

). Wolff-Kishner reduction of hecogenin (
1
) and gentrogenin (
7
) gave tigogenin (
13
) and diosgenin (
22
), respectively. Similarly, smilagenin (
17
) was formed after reduction of gloriogenin (
3
) (

). Further, acetylation of sapogenins is a classic method of producing crystalline acetates having sharp melting points (

; 

; 

).

As the number of sugars and branching points increase, the NMR spectra of saponins become more complicated. Acid hydrolysis has been widely used for identification of monosaccharide components of saponins of 

Agave

. A typical acid hydrolysis protocol involves refluxing the saponin in the presence of 1 M HCl-methanol (

) or 1 M sulfuric acid in 50% ethanol for 3 

4 h. The reaction mixture is diluted with water to yield the (crystalline) aglycone which precipitates, while the monosaccharides remain in solution (

). The identity, absolute configuration and numbers of monosaccharides were established by various chromatographic methods (
Table S3
).

The 
type
of glycosidic linkage between the monosaccharides of the sugar chain of saponins was determined by methylation analysis. Saponins are methylated using a) dimethyl sulfoxide/lithium methylsulfinyl carbanion/methyl iodide (Hakomori s method) (

) or b) sodium hydride/methyl iodide in hexamethylphoshoric triamide (HPMA) or dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) (

). The permethylated products were hydrolyzed using hydrochloric acid, perchloric acid or trifluoroacetic acid. Individual methylated monosaccharides were identified by a) GLC or NMR of isolated compounds (

) b) paper chromatography (

) or c) analyzed as partial alditol acetates by GC-MS (

). 
