Agave
plants

have been used for their medicinal properties since times immemorial. Most ethnopharmacological uses of these plants can be attributed to their antimicrobial and antioxidant activities (

; 

). These plants are used in the treatment of gastrointestinal and urological disorders, dysentery, wound infections, cancer, hypertension and diabetes (

; 

; 

). Some biological activities of 

Agave

compounds (and extracts) are scientifically proven and mechanistically studied with the help of various 
in vitro
and 
in vivo
assays and models (

; 

; 

; 

; Yokosuka et al., 2009). These activities are of medicinal and pharmacological significance or of agricultural importance.

By virtue of their capacity to alter membrane permeability, saponins have powerful hemolytic activity (

; 

). These compounds have an amphipathic (bipolar) structure with a hydrophobic sapogenin and a hydrophilic sugar moiety and have an affinity for sterols on membranes of erythrocytes (

). The hemolytic effects of spirostanol (
110
) and furostanol (
129
) glycosides having the same sugar chain at C-3 of the sapogenin were evaluated. Compound 
129
demonstrated a complete absence of hemolytic effects, while compound 
110
caused significant hemolysis in an erythrocyte suspension. Therefore, it was inferred that since 
129
is a bidesmosidic saponin and the sugar moieties were distantly placed in the structure (at C-3 and C-26), it reduced the overall hydrophobicity of the compound. Hence, loss of amphipathic character led to loss of activity (

). These results were further verified by absence of hemolytic effects in the compounds 
132
and 
140
(

; 

).

Cytotoxicity of saponins isolated from
A. utahensis
was evaluated using HL-60 human promyelocytic leukemia cells. Compounds 41 and 54 exhibited cytotoxicity with an IC 50 of 4.9
g/mL. The C-2 hydroxyl and C-12 carbonyl moieties reduced the cytotoxicity of these compounds (Yokosuka et al., 2009;
). These compounds mediated cell death by apoptosis. Caspase-3 was found to be activated when HL-60 cells were treated with 41 and 54 (20
g/mL for 6 h) (Yokosuka et al., 2009).

Results of cytotoxicity studies of the compounds isolated from the methanolic extract of
A. sisalana
leaves implied that the sugar moiety plays a crucial role in bioactivity of saponins. Saponins ( 66 , 104 , 105 and 137 ) are more cytotoxic as compared to the sapogenins ( 1 , 2 , 13 , 14 and 20 ) (
). The sequence and number of the sugar units present in the sugar chain of the saponin also affected cytotoxicity. The diglycosides ( 36 and 37 ) were less cytotoxic, as compared to the hexasaccharides (
107
109
) (
).

Mouse ear edema model (edema induction by 12- O - tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate, TPA) was used to evaluate the antiinflammatory potential of the acetone extract of the leaves of
Agave tequilana
,
A. americana
and
Agave angustifolia ( Monterrosas-Brisson et al., 2013 )
. The extract of
A. americana
showed maximum activity with 81% inhibition of auricular edema at a dose of 6 mg / ear. Cantalasaponin-1 ( 39 ) was purified from the extract of
A. americana
by a bioassay-guided fractionation and was tested for its antiinflammatory activity. It showed a 90% inhibition of ear edema at a dose of 2.0 mg per ear (
). Hecogenin ( 1 ) also showed antiinflammatory activity in carrageenin-induced paw edema model (
). Acute inflammatory model of topical edema on mouse ear skin (induction by application of croton oil) was also used to evaluate the antiinflammatory potential of saponins (
). A comparison of the antiinflammatory activity of spirostanol ( 110 ) and furostanol ( 129 ) glycosides revealed that 110 suppressed the edema significantly and the activity was comparable to the reference drugs (indomethacin and dexamethasone). These results pointed toward the involvement of rings E and F of the spirostane nucleus in the bioactivity (
) which used the capillary permeability assay for the evaluation of antiinflammatory activity ( Fig. 2 ). Compound 140 also showed a signifi- cant inhibition of an acetic acid-induced increase in capillary permeability (
).

Hecogenin ( 1 ), a steroidal sapogenin with a spectrum of pharmacological activities, is perhaps the most studied sapogenin of
Agave
. It is an important precursor of steroid hormones (
). Hecogenin acetate ( 1a ) exhibited considerable antihyperalgesic activity in case of hyperalgesia induced in mice by carrageenan, TNF- a , dopamine and PGE 2 . It reduced levels of proinflammatory cytokines, such as IL-1 b , and inhibited Fos-like expression in the spinal cord (
). Another study reported the antinociceptive activity of 1a and evaluated the involvement of periaqueductal gray in the antinociception mechanism. The systemic administration of 1a to male Swiss Webster mice increased Fos expression in the periaqueductal gray and thereby produced antinociception mediated by opioid receptors and by activation of descending pain-inhibitory pathways (
).

Hecogenin (
1
) exhibited a gastroprotective effect in ethanol-and indomethacin-induced gastric ulcer models of Swiss mice. It decreased lipid peroxidation and nitrite levels and increased COX-2 expression. The effect of hecogenin (
1
) was attributed to opening of K 

ATP
channels and prostaglandin synthesis. It also showed antiinflammatory activity by decreasing release of myeloperoxidase from human neutrophils 
in vitro
(

).


Agave

is a suitable crop for natural and cultivated environments to withstand the stress of climate change and global warming (

). In view of a number of bioactivities of saponins (Gl-Ustndagand 

; 

; 

), there is a continuing search for plants with new saponins or known saponins in higher content. With this objective, various species of the genus 

Agave

have received attention of natural products chemists.

Plant taxonomy based on morphological characteristics has inherent disadvantages (

; 

). Hence, there has been a need for better and more representative tools for plant identification (

). The presence of unique plant secondary metabolites or unique structural features of common natural plant products provides an important tool for chemotaxonomy (

; 

). Chemotaxonomy has advantages over molecular taxonomy for systematics of 

plants (
